</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff;padding-left: 10pt; text-indent: -10pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;	" align="left" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #ffffff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Leasehold improvements</font></font></td>
<td style="background-color: #ffffff;border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff; border-right: none"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="background-color: #ffffff;border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff;padding-left: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;	" align="left" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #ffffff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Lower of 15 years or lease term</font></font></td>
<td style="background-color: #ffffff;border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff; border-right: none"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="background-color: #ffffff;border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #ffffff;padding-left: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;	" align="center" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #ffffff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">0%</font></font></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff;padding-left: 10pt; text-indent: -10pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #cceeff;	" align="left" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #cceeff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Buildings on leased land</font></font></td>
<td style="background-color: #cceeff;border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff; border-right: none"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="background-color: #cceeff;border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff;padding-left: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #cceeff;	" align="left" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #cceeff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Lease term</font></font></td>
<td style="background-color: #cceeff;border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff; border-right: none"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="background-color: #cceeff;border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff;padding-left: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #cceeff;	" align="center" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #cceeff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">0%</font></font></td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>
</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Property under capital leases are recorded at an amount equal to the present value of future minimum lease payments computed on the basis of our incremental borrowing rate, or, when known, the interest rate implicit in the lease. Amortization of property under capital leases is on a straight-line basis over the expected useful life and is included in depreciation and amortization expense.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We record impairment losses on long-lived assets used in operations when events and circumstances indicate that the assets may be impaired and the undiscounted future cash flows estimated to be generated by these assets are less than the assets&rsquo; net book value. If impairment occurs, the loss is measured by comparing the fair value of the asset to its carrying amount. Impairment losses are recorded in depreciation and amortization expense.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In 2007, we sold three Airbus A320 aircraft, which resulted in gains of $7&nbsp;million. In 2006, we sold five Airbus A320 aircraft, which resulted in gains of $12&nbsp;million. The gains on our sales of Airbus A320 aircraft are included in other operating expenses. In December&nbsp;2005, we discontinued development of a maintenance and inventory tracking system and consequently wrote off $6&nbsp;million in capitalized costs. Each of these items is included in other operating expenses.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Restricted Cash:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Restricted cash primarily consists of security deposits and performance bonds for aircraft and facility leases and funds held in escrow for estimated workers&rsquo; compensation obligations.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Passenger Revenues:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Passenger revenue is recognized, net of the taxes that we are required to collect from our customers including federal transportation taxes, security taxes and airport facility charges, when the transportation is provided or after the ticket or customer credit (issued upon payment of a change fee) expires. Tickets sold but not yet recognized as revenue and unexpired credits are included in air traffic liability.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">LiveTV Revenues and Expenses:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We account for LiveTV&rsquo;s revenues and expenses related to the sale of hardware, maintenance of hardware, and programming services provided, as a single unit in accordance with Emerging Issues Task Force Issue 00-21, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Accounting for Revenue Arrangements with Multiple Deliverables</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">. Revenues and expenses related to these components are recognized ratably over the service periods which currently extend through 2014. Customer advances are included in other liabilities.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Airframe and Engine Maintenance and Repair:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Regular airframe maintenance for owned and leased flight equipment is charged to expense as incurred unless covered by a third-party services contract. In 2006 and 2005, we commenced separate services agreements covering the scheduled and unscheduled repair of airframe line replacement unit components and the engines on our Airbus A320 aircraft. These agreements, which range from ten to 15 years, require monthly payments at rates based either on the number of cycles each aircraft was operated during each month or the number of flight hours each engine was operated during each month, subject to annual escalations. These payments are expensed as the related flight hours or cycles are incurred.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Advertising Costs:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Advertising costs, which are included in sales and marketing, are expensed as incurred. Advertising expense in 2007, 2006 and 2005 was $41&nbsp;million, $40&nbsp;million and $35&nbsp;million, respectively.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">50</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page51"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Loyalty Program:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We account for our customer loyalty program, TrueBlue Flight Gratitude, by recording a liability for the estimated incremental cost for points outstanding and awards we expect to be redeemed. We adjust this liability, which is included in air traffic liability, based on points earned and redeemed as well as changes in the estimated incremental costs associated with providing travel.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We also sell points in TrueBlue to third parties. A portion of these point sales is deferred and recognized as passenger revenue when transportation is provided. The remaining portion, which is the excess of the total sales proceeds over the estimated fair value of the transportation to be provided, is recognized in other revenue at the time of sale. Deferred revenue for points not redeemed is recorded upon expiration.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Income Taxes:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We account for income taxes utilizing the liability method. Deferred income taxes are recognized for the tax consequences of temporary differences between the tax and financial statement reporting bases of assets and liabilities. A valuation allowance for net deferred tax assets is provided unless realizability is judged by us to be more likely than not.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">Stock-Based Compensation:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Effective January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2006, we adopted the provisions of Statement of Financial Accounting Standards 123(R), </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Share-Based Payment</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">, and related interpretations, or SFAS 123(R), to account for stock-based compensation using the modified prospective transition method and therefore will not restate our prior period results. SFAS 123(R) supersedes Accounting Principles Board Opinion 25, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Accounting for Stock Issued to Employees</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">, or APB 25, and revises guidance in Statement of Financial Accounting Standards 123, </font><font style="
opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Accounting for Stock-Based Compensation</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">, or SFAS 123. Among other things, SFAS 123(R) requires that compensation expense be recognized in the financial statements for share-based awards based on the grant date fair value of those awards. The modified prospective transition method applies to (a) unvested stock options under our amended and restated 2002 Stock Incentive Plan, or the 2002 Plan, and issuances under our Crewmember Stock Purchase Plan, as amended, or CSPP, outstanding as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2005 based on the grant date fair value estimated in accordance with the pro forma provisions of SFAS 123, and (b) any new share-based awards granted subsequent to December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2005, based on the grant-date fair value estimated in accordance with the provisions of SFAS 123(R). Additionally, stock-based compensation expense includes an estimate for pre-vesting forfeiture
s and is recognized over the requisite service periods of the awards on a straight-line basis, which is generally commensurate with the vesting term.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Prior to January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2006, we accounted for our stock-based compensation plans in accordance with APB 25 and related interpretations. Accordingly, compensation expense for a stock option grant was recognized only if the exercise price was less than the market value of our common stock on the grant date. Compensation expense was not recognized under our CSPP as the purchase price of the stock issued thereunder was not less than 85% of the lower of the fair market value of our common stock at the beginning of each offering period or at the end of each purchase period under the plan.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">SFAS 123(R) requires the benefits associated with tax deductions in excess of recognized compensation cost to be reported as a financing cash flow rather than as an operating cash flow as previously required. In 2007 and 2006, we did not record any excess tax benefit generated from option exercises.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">51</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>

<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The table below summarizes the impact on our results of operations for the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 and 2006 of outstanding stock options and restricted stock units under our 2002 Plan and issuances under our CSPP recognized under the provisions of SFAS 123(R) (in millions, except per share data):</font>
</p>

<tr>
<td style="font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff;padding-left: 10pt; text-indent: -10pt; padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #cceeff;	" align="left" valign="bottom" colspan="1"><font style="font-family: serif; font-size: 10pt; line-height:12pt; color: #000000; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal;background-color: #cceeff;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Stock-based compensation expense:</font></font></td>
<td style="background-color: #cceeff;border-bottom: 1px solid #cceeff; border-right: none"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1" height="1"></td>

<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Prior to our adoption of SFAS 123(R), we presented unearned compensation as a separate component of stockholders&rsquo; equity. In accordance with the provisions of SFAS 123(R), on January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2006, we reclassified unearned compensation to additional paid-in capital on our balance sheet. The following table illustrates the effect on net loss and loss per common share as if we had applied the fair value method to measure stock-based compensation, which is described more fully in Note 7, as required under the disclosure provisions of SFAS 123 for the year ended December 31, 2005 (in millions, except per share amounts):</font>

</div>
</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In December&nbsp;2005, we accelerated the vesting of 19.9&nbsp;million stock options, representing 64% of the options then outstanding. This action resulted in non-cash, stock-based compensation expense of $7&nbsp;million in 2005. It also resulted in an increase of $72&nbsp;million, net of tax, in the pro forma employee stock option stock-based compensation expense shown above. The decision to accelerate vesting of these options was made primarily to avoid recognizing the related compensation cost in our future consolidated financial statements upon our adoption of SFAS 123(R).</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Our policy is to issue new shares for purchases under our CSPP and issuances under our 2002 Plan.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: bold; font-style: italic;">New Accounting Standards:</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In September&nbsp;2006, the FASB issued Statement of Financial Accounting Standards 157, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Fair Value&nbsp;Measurements, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">or SFAS 157, which defines fair value, establishes a framework for measuring fair value and requires enhanced disclosures about fair value measurements. SFAS 157 requires companies </font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">52</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page53"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">
to disclose the fair value of their financial instruments according to a fair value hierarchy, as defined, and may require them to provide additional disclosures based on that hierarchy. SFAS 157 is effective for financial statements issued for fiscal years beginning after November&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2007 and interim periods within those fiscal years. On November&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2007, the FASB partially deferred the effective date of FAS 157 to fiscal years (and interim periods within those fiscal years) beginning after November&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2008 for certain non financial assets and non financial liabilities. We have considered the impact of our adoption of SFAS 157 and the related partial deferral and we do not believe it will result in a material cumulative effect adjustment on our consolidated financial statements when adopted on January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2008. However, we believe it will likely be required to provide additional disclosures as part of future financial statements beginning with the first quarter 2008
.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 2&mdash;Long-term Debt, Short-term Borrowings and Capital Lease Obligations</font>
</p>

<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(2)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In November&nbsp;2006, we completed a public offering of $124&nbsp;million of pass-through certificates, to finance certain of our owned aircraft spare parts. Separate trusts were established for each class of these certificates. The entire principal amount of the Class G-1 and Class B-1 certificates is scheduled to be paid in a lump sum on the applicable maturity date. The interest rate for all certificates is based on three month LIBOR plus a margin. Interest is payable quarterly.</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="602">
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(3)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In November&nbsp;2004 and March&nbsp;2004, we completed public offerings of $498&nbsp;million and $431&nbsp;million, respectively, of pass-through certificates, to finance the purchase of 28 new Airbus A320 aircraft delivered through 2005. Separate trusts were established for each class of these certificates. Principal payments are required on the Class G-1 and Class C certificates quarterly. The entire principal amount of the Class G-2 certificates is scheduled to be paid in a lump sum on the applicable maturity dates. The interest rate for all certificates is based on three month LIBOR plus a margin. Interest is payable quarterly.</font></td>
</tr>

<a name="page54"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="602">
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">
construction and other costs. We have recorded the issuance of $39&nbsp;million (net of $1&nbsp;million discount) and $45&nbsp;million (net of $2&nbsp;million discount), respectively, as long-term debt on our consolidated balance sheet because we have issued a guarantee of the debt payments on the bonds. This fixed rate debt is secured by leasehold mortgages of our airport facilities.</font></td>
</tr>

<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="602">
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(5)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In March&nbsp;2005, we completed a public offering of $250&nbsp;million aggregate principal amount of 3&frac34;% convertible unsecured debentures due 2035, which are currently convertible into 14.6&nbsp;million shares of our common stock at a price of approximately $17.10 per share, or 58.4795 shares per $1,000 principal amount of debentures, subject to further adjustment. Upon conversion, we have the right to deliver, in lieu of shares of our common stock, cash or a combination of cash and shares of our common stock. At any time, we may irrevocably elect to satisfy our conversion obligation with respect to the principal amount of the debentures to be converted with a combination of cash and shares of our common stock.</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:20pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">At any time on or after March&nbsp;20,&nbsp;2010, we may redeem any of the debentures for cash at a redemption price of 100% of their principal amount, plus accrued and unpaid interest. Holders may require us to repurchase the debentures for cash at a repurchase price equal to 100% of their principal amount plus accrued and unpaid interest, if any, on March&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2010, 2015, 2020, 2025 and 2030, or at any time prior to their maturity upon the occurrence of a specified designated event.&nbsp;Interest is payable semi-annually on March&nbsp;15 and September&nbsp;15.</font>
</p>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="602">
<tr>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(6)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In July&nbsp;2003, we sold $175&nbsp;million aggregate principal amount of 3&frac12;% convertible unsecured notes due 2033, which are currently convertible into 6.2&nbsp;million shares of our common stock at a price of approximately $28.33 per share, or 35.2941 shares per $1,000 principal amount of notes, subject to further adjustment and certain conditions on conversion. At any time on or after July&nbsp;18,&nbsp;2008, we may redeem the notes for cash at a redemption price of 100% of their principal amount, plus accrued and unpaid interest. Holders may require us to repurchase all or a portion of their notes for cash on July&nbsp;15 of 2008, 2013, 2018, 2023, and 2028 or upon the occurrence of certain designated events at a repurchase price equal to the principal amount of the notes, plus accrued and unpaid interest. We ha
ve classified these notes as current at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 since we believe that the holders will put them back to us on their first repurchase date, July&nbsp;15,&nbsp;2008. Interest is payable semi-annually on January&nbsp;15 and July&nbsp;15.</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="602">

<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(7)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We entered into capital lease agreements for two Airbus A320 aircraft in each of 2007 and 2006. At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 and 2006, these aircraft are included in property and equipment at a cost of $152&nbsp;million and $75&nbsp;million, respectively, with accumulated amortization of $4&nbsp;million and $1&nbsp;million, respectively. The future minimum lease payments under these noncancelable leases are $15&nbsp;million per year through 2011, $14&nbsp;million in 2012 and $152&nbsp;million in the years thereafter. Included in the future minimum lease payments is $78&nbsp;million representing interest, resulting in a present value of capital leases of $148&nbsp;million with a current portion of $6&nbsp;million and a long-term portion of $142&nbsp;million.</font></td>
</tr>

<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We have utilized funding facilities to finance aircraft predelivery deposits. These facilities allow for borrowings of up to $77&nbsp;million, of which $34&nbsp;million was unused as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007. Commitment fees are 0.5% per annum on the average unused portion of the facilities. The weighted average interest rate on these outstanding short-term borrowings at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 and 2006 was 6.7% and 7.1%, respectively.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We have no financial covenants associated with our debt agreements. We are subject to certain collateral ratio requirements in our spare parts pass-through certificates and spare engine financing </font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">54</p>

<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">
issued in November&nbsp;2006 and December&nbsp;2007, respectively. If we fail to maintain these collateral ratios, we will be required to provide additional collateral or redeem some or all of the equipment notes so that the ratios return to compliance. In 2007, we sold three owned Airbus A320 aircraft for $100&nbsp;million and repaid $68&nbsp;million in associated debt. Aircraft, engines, predelivery deposits and other equipment and facilities having a net book value of $3.52&nbsp;billion at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 were pledged as security under various loan agreements. Cash payments of interest, net of capitalized interest, aggregated $175&nbsp;million, $133&nbsp;million and $79&nbsp;million in 2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively.</font>
</p>

</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The estimated fair values of our publicly held long-term debt were based on quoted market prices. The fair value of our non-public debt was estimated using discounted cash flow analysis based on our current borrowing rates for instruments with similar terms. The fair values of our other financial instruments approximate their carrying values.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 3&mdash;Operating Leases</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We lease aircraft, as well as airport terminal space, other airport facilities, office space and other equipment, which expire in various years through 2035. Total rental expense for all operating leases in 2007, 2006 and 2005 was $225&nbsp;million, $190&nbsp;million and $137&nbsp;million, respectively. We have $26&nbsp;million in assets that serve as collateral for letters of credit related to certain of our leases, which are included in restricted cash.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">At December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 53 of the 134 aircraft we operated were leased under operating leases, with initial lease term expiration dates ranging from 2009 to 2025. Five of the 53 aircraft operating leases have variable-rate rent payments based on LIBOR. Leases for 46 of our aircraft can generally be renewed at rates based on fair market value at the end of the lease term for one or two years. We have purchase options in 44 of our aircraft leases at the end of the lease term at fair market value and a one-time option during the term at amounts that are expected to approximate fair market value. During 2007, we entered into sale and leaseback transactions for seven EMBRAER 190 aircraft acquired during the year that are being accounted for as operating leases. We have deferred $4&nbsp;million in gains related to these sale and leaseback transactions, which are being recognized on a straight-line basis over the related 18-year lease terms as a reduction to ai
rcraft rent expense. During 2007 we also returned one leased A320 aircraft to its lessor.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">55</p>

<td style="font-size: 10pt;  line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 3px solid #cceeff;padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #cceeff; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; " valign="bottom" align="left"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1"></td>

</div>
</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We hold variable interests in 44 of our 53 aircraft operating leases, which are owned by single owner trusts whose sole purpose is to purchase, finance and lease these aircraft to us. Since we do not participate in these trusts and we are not at risk for losses, we are not required to include these trusts in our consolidated financial statements. Our maximum exposure is the remaining lease payments, which are reflected in the future minimum lease payments in the table above.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 4&mdash;Assets Constructed for Others</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In November&nbsp;2005, we executed a lease agreement with the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, or PANYNJ, for the construction and operation of a new terminal at JFK.&nbsp;Under this lease, we are responsible for construction of a 635,000 square foot 26-gate terminal, a parking garage, roadways and an AirTrain Connector, all of which will be owned by the PANYNJ and which are collectively referred to as the Project.&nbsp;The lease term ends on the earlier of the thirtieth anniversary of the date of beneficial occupancy of the new terminal or November&nbsp;21,&nbsp;2039. We have a one-time early termination option five years prior to the end of the scheduled lease term.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The aggregate cost of the Project is estimated at $740&nbsp;million and is expected to be completed in late 2008. We are making various payments under the lease, including ground rents for the new terminal site which began on lease execution, and facility rents that are anticipated to commence upon the date of beneficial occupancy. The facility rents are based on the number of passengers enplaned out of the new terminal, subject to annual minimums. The PANYNJ reimburses us for the costs of constructing the Project in accordance with the lease, except for approximately $80&nbsp;million in leasehold improvements that will be provided by us.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We have evaluated this lease and have concluded that we bear substantially all of the construction period risk, as defined in Emerging Issues Task Force Issue 97-10, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">The Effect of Lessee Involvement in Asset Construction</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">. As a result, we are considered the owner of the Project for financial reporting purposes only and are required to reflect an asset and liability for in-process construction related to the Project on our balance sheets. To date, we have paid $457&nbsp;million in Project costs and have capitalized $34&nbsp;million in interest, which are reflected as Assets Constructed for Others in the accompanying consolidated balance sheets. Reimbursements from the PANYNJ and financing charges totaled $452&nbsp;million through December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 and are reflected as Construction Obligation in our consolidat
ed balance sheets net of $14&nbsp;million in scheduled prepayments to the PANYNJ. Following the construction period, we do not currently anticipate that we will have satisfied the sale and leaseback accounting criteria outlined in Statement of Financial Accounting Standards No. 98, </font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Accounting for Leases</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">, due to our continuing involvement in the property; therefore, the completed project and related liability will remain on our balance sheets and be accounted for as a financing.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Assets Constructed for Others will be amortized over the shorter of the lease term or their economic life. Facility rents will be recorded as debt service on the Construction Obligation, with the portion not relating to interest reducing the principal balance. Ground rents are being recognized on a straight-line basis over the lease term and are reflected in the future minimum lease payments table included in Note 3. Minimum estimated facility payments, including escalations, associated with this lease are estimated to be $6&nbsp;million in 2008, $22&nbsp;million in 2009, $30&nbsp;million in 2010, $35&nbsp;million in 2011, $38&nbsp;million in 2012 and $892&nbsp;million thereafter.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">56</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page57"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 5&mdash;Stockholders&rsquo; Equity</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Our authorized shares of capital stock consist of 500&nbsp;million shares of common stock and 25&nbsp;million shares of preferred stock. The holders of our common stock are entitled to one vote per share on all matters which require a vote by the Company&rsquo;s stockholders as set forth in our Amended and Restated Certificate of Incorporation and Bylaws.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We distributed 57&nbsp;million shares of common stock in connection with our December&nbsp;2005 three-for-two stock split. All common share and per share data for periods presented in the accompanying consolidated financial statements and notes thereto give effect to this stock split.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">In November&nbsp;2005, we completed a public offering of 12.9&nbsp;million shares of our common stock at $12.00 per share, raising net proceeds of $153&nbsp;million, after deducting discounts and commissions paid to the underwriters and other expenses incurred in connection with the offering.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Pursuant to our amended Stockholder Rights Agreement, which became effective in February&nbsp;2002, each share of common stock has attached to it a right and, until the rights expire or are redeemed, each new share of common stock issued by the Company will include one right. Upon the occurrence of certain events, each right entitles the holder to purchase one one-thousandth of a share of Series A participating preferred stock at an exercise price of $35.55, subject to further adjustment. The rights become exercisable only after any person or group acquires beneficial ownership of 15% or more (25% or more in the case of certain specified stockholders) of the Company&rsquo;s outstanding common stock or commences a tender or exchange offer that would result in such person or group acquiring beneficial ownership of 15% or more (25% or more in the case of certain stockholders) of the Company&rsquo;s common stock. If after the rights become exercisable, the Company i
s involved in a merger or other business combination or sells more than 50% of its assets or earning power, each right will entitle its holder (other than the acquiring person or group) to receive common stock of the acquiring company having a market value of twice the exercise price of the rights. The rights expire on April&nbsp;17,&nbsp;2012 and may be redeemed by the Company at a price of $.01&nbsp;per right prior to the time they become exercisable.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">As of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, we had a total of 83.2&nbsp;million shares of our common stock reserved for issuance under our CSPP, our 2002 Plan and for our convertible debt.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">

<td style="font-size: 10pt;  line-height:12pt; color: #000000; border-bottom: 3px solid #ffffff;padding-top: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff; font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; " valign="bottom" align="left"><img src="spacer.gif" width="1"></td>

</div>
</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">For each of the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 2006 and 2005, a total 20.8&nbsp;million shares issuable upon conversion of our convertible debt were excluded from the diluted earnings per share calculation since the assumed conversions would be anti-dilutive. We also excluded 24.7&nbsp;million, 31.1&nbsp;million and 31.1&nbsp;million shares issuable upon exercise of outstanding stock options for the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively, from the diluted earnings (loss) per share computation since their exercise price was greater than the average market price of our common stock or they were otherwise anti-dilutive.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">57</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page58"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 7&mdash;Stock-Based Compensation</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Fair Value Assumptions:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We use a Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing model to estimate the fair value of share-based awards under SFAS 123(R) for issuances under our CSPP and our 2002 Plan. This is the same valuation technique we previously used for pro forma disclosures under SFAS 123. The Black-Scholes-Merton option pricing model incorporates various and highly subjective assumptions, including expected term and expected volatility. We have reviewed our historical pattern of option exercises and have determined that meaningful differences in option exercise activity existed among employee job categories. Therefore, for all stock options granted after January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2006, we have categorized these awards into three groups of employees for valuation purposes. We have determined there were no meaningful differences in employee activity under 
our CSPP due to the broad-based nature of the plan.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We estimate the expected term of options granted using an implied life derived from the results of a lattice model, which incorporates our historical exercise and post-vesting employment termination patterns, which we believe are representative of future behavior. The expected term for our CSPP valuation is based on the length of each purchase period as measured at the beginning of the offering period.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">We estimate the expected volatility of our common stock at the grant date using a blend of 75%&nbsp;historical volatility of our common stock and 25% implied volatility of two-year publicly traded options on our common stock as of the option grant date. Our decision to use a blend of historical and implied volatility was based upon the volume of actively traded options on our common stock and our belief that historical volatility alone may not be completely representative of future stock price trends.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Our risk-free interest rate assumption is determined using the Federal Reserve nominal rates for U.S. Treasury zero-coupon bonds with maturities similar to those of the expected term of the award being valued. We have never paid any cash dividends on our common stock and we do not anticipate paying any cash dividends in the foreseeable future. Therefore, we assumed an expected dividend yield of zero.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Additionally, SFAS 123(R) requires us to estimate pre-vesting option forfeitures at the time of grant and periodically revise those estimates in subsequent periods if actual forfeitures differ from those estimates. We record stock-based compensation expense only for those awards expected to vest using an estimated forfeiture rate based on our historical pre-vesting forfeiture data. Previously, we accounted for forfeitures as they occurred under the pro forma disclosure provisions of SFAS 123 for periods prior to 2006.</font>
</p>

<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Unrecognized stock-based compensation expense was approximately $26&nbsp;million as of December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, relating to a total of eight million unvested stock options and restricted stock </font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">58</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page59"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">
units under our 2002 Plan and purchase rights under our CSPP. We expect to recognize this stock-based compensation expense over a weighted average period of approximately three years. The total fair value of stock options vested during the years ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 2006 and 2005 was approximately $6&nbsp;million, $2&nbsp;million and $126&nbsp;million, respectively.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Crewmember Stock Purchase Plan:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Our CSPP, which is available to all employees, had 5.1&nbsp;million shares of our common stock initially reserved for issuance at its inception in April&nbsp;2002. The reserve automatically increases each January by an amount equal to 3% of the total number of shares of our common stock outstanding on the last trading day in December of the prior calendar year. In no event will any such annual increase exceed 9.1&nbsp;million shares. The plan will terminate no later than the last business day of April&nbsp;2012.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The plan has a series of successive overlapping 24-month or 6-month offering periods, with a new offering period beginning on the first business day of May and November each year. Employees can only join an offering period on the start date and participate in one offering period at a time. Employees may contribute up to 10% of their pay, through payroll deductions, toward the purchase of common stock. Purchase dates occur on the last business day of April and October each year.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Effective May&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2007, all new CSPP participation is considered non-compensatory following the elimination of the 24-month offering period and the reduction of the purchase price discount from 15% to 5%. Participants previously enrolled will be allowed to continue to purchase shares in their current compensatory offering periods until these offering periods expire in 2008. The modification to our CSPP plan was done in conjunction with the modifications to our employee retirement plan discussed in Note 10.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Prior to the 2007 amendment, if the fair market value per share of our common stock on any purchase date within a particular offering period is less than the fair market value per share on the start date of that offering period, then the participants in that offering period were automatically transferred and enrolled in the new two-year offering period which began on the next business day following such purchase date and the related purchase of shares. During 2006 and 2005, certain participants were automatically transferred and enrolled in new offering periods due to decreases in our stock price.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Should we be acquired by merger or sale of substantially all of our assets or more than 50% of our outstanding voting securities, then all outstanding purchase rights will automatically be exercised immediately prior to the effective date of the acquisition at a price equal to either a) the lower of 85% of the fair market value per share on the start date of the offering period in which the participant is enrolled or 85% of the fair market value per share immediately prior to the acquisition or b) 95% of the fair market value per share immediately prior to the acquisition.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff">

<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: 18pt; padding-left: 0pt;"><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">(1)</font></td>
<td align="left" valign="top" style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size: 10pt; padding-bottom: 6pt;   width: pt; "><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">On January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2008, the number of shares reserved for issuance was increased by 5,447,803 shares.</font></td>

<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic;">Stock Incentive Plan:</font><font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2002 Plan, which includes stock options issued during 1999 through 2001 under a previous plan as well as all options issued since, provides for incentive and non-qualified stock options to be granted to certain employees and members of our Board of Directors. The 2002 Plan became effective following our initial public offering. Prior to January&nbsp;1,&nbsp;2006, stock options under the 2002 Plan became exercisable when vested, which occurred in annual installments of three to seven years. For issuances under the 2002 Plan beginning in 2006, we revised the vesting terms so </font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">59</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page60"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">
that all options granted now vest in equal installments over a period of three or five years, or upon the occurrence of a change in control. All options issued under the 2002 Plan expire ten years from the date of grant. Our policy is to grant options with the exercise price equal to the market price of the underlying common stock on the date of grant. The number of shares reserved for issuance under the 2002 Plan will automatically increase each January by an amount equal to 4% of the total number of shares of our common stock outstanding on the last trading day in December of the prior calendar year. In no event will any such annual increase exceed 12.2&nbsp;million shares. The 2002 Plan will terminate no later than December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2011.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff">

</div>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The total intrinsic value, determined as of the date of exercise, of options exercised during the twelve months ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 2006 and 2005 was $15&nbsp;million, $25&nbsp;million and $19&nbsp;million, respectively. We received $8&nbsp;million, $11&nbsp;million and $6&nbsp;million in cash from option exercises for the twelve months ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, 2006 and 2005, respectively.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">During 2007, we also began issuing restricted stock units under the 2002 Plan. These awards will vest in annual installments over three years. During the year ended December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, we granted 71,418 restricted stock units at a weighted average grant date fair value of $10.42, none of which are vested and all of which remain outstanding at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">SFAS 123(R) requires that deferred taxes be recognized on temporary differences that arise with respect to stock-based compensation attributable to nonqualified stock options and awards. However, no tax benefit is recognized for stock-based compensation attributable to incentive stock options (ISO) or CSPP shares until there is a disqualifying disposition, if any, for income tax purposes. A portion of our stock-based compensation is attributable to ISO and CSPP shares therefore, our effective tax rate is subject to fluctuation.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt; text-align: center; width: 456pt;">60</p>
<br>
<hr width="760" style="padding-left: 0pt;" align="left">
<br>
<DIV STYLE="page-break-before: always;"></DIV><BR>
<a name="page61"></a><font style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:8pt;  text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 10pt; background-color: #ffffff"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></font>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 8&mdash;LiveTV</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Purchased technology, which is an intangible asset related to our September&nbsp;2002 acquisition of the membership interests of LiveTV, is being amortized over seven years based on the average number of aircraft expected to be in service as of the date of acquisition. Projected amortization expense is $13&nbsp;million and $8&nbsp;million in 2008 and 2009, respectively.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Through December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, LiveTV had installed in-flight entertainment systems for other airlines on 372 aircraft and had firm commitments for installations on 314 additional aircraft scheduled to be installed through 2012, with options for 182 additional installations through 2017. Revenues in 2007, 2006 and 2005 were $40&nbsp;million, $29&nbsp;million and $19&nbsp;million, respectively. Deferred profit on hardware sales and advance deposits for future hardware sales are included in long term liabilities in our consolidated balance sheets was $29&nbsp;million and $27&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 and 2006, respectively. Deferred profit to be recognized on installations completed through December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007 will be approximately $7&nbsp;million per year through 2009, $2&nbsp;million through 2014.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:bold;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top: 12pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 0pt; padding-bottom: 0pt; background-color: #ffffff;">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Note 9&mdash;Income Taxes</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">

</p>

<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">Cash payments for income taxes were zero in 2007 and 2006, and $1&nbsp;million in 2005.</font>
</p>
<p style="font-family:serif;font-weight:normal;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;  width: 456pt; text-align: left; font-style: normal; line-height: 12pt; padding-top:6pt; padding-left:0pt; padding-right:0pt; padding-bottom: 6pt; margin: 0pt; text-indent: 20pt; background-color: #ffffff">
<font style="opacity:100; position:relative; ">The net deferred taxes below include a current net deferred tax asset of $41&nbsp;million and a long-term net deferred tax liability of $192&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2007, and a current net deferred tax asset of $25&nbsp;million and a long-term net deferred tax liability of $136&nbsp;million at December&nbsp;31,&nbsp;2006.</font>
</p>
